{"title":"Knowledge Graph Self-Supervised Rationalization for Recommendation","domain":"IR_REC","seeds":[{"problem":"Knowledge graphs contain many noisy or task-irrelevant triplets, making it hard for KG-enhanced recommenders to focus on the knowledge that truly explains user-item interactions.","method":"KGRec learns rationale scores for KG triplets via an attentive rationale weighting function inspired by heterogeneous graph transformers. It computes attention over triplets using relation-aware keys (element-wise product of relation and tail embeddings) and normalizes scores across a head’s neighbors to yield comparable importance. These rationale scores are then injected to weight heterogeneous knowledge aggregation, emphasizing high-importance neighbors during item (and user) representation learning."},{"problem":"Generative self-supervision on KGs often relies on random masking, which fails to highlight task-relevant knowledge and can be sensitive to KG noise.","method":"KGRec introduces a rationale-aware masked autoencoder: it derives globally comparable importance γ(h,r,t) by scaling softmax rationale scores with the head’s degree and adds Gumbel noise for robust top‑k selection. High‑γ triplets are masked to form an augmented KG, embeddings are computed on the remaining graph, and a relation-aware dot‑product decoder reconstructs the masked edges. This masking‑reconstruction forces the model to rebuild crucial connections and distill informative KG rationales for recommendation."},{"problem":"Cross-view contrastive learning between the KG and user–item interaction graph can be degraded by noisy edges and false negatives, weakening alignment between knowledge and collaborative signals.","method":"KGRec performs rationale-aware augmentation for both views: it prunes low‑score KG triplets and down-weights/drops user–item edges based on the mean rationale scores of items’ linked triplets via multinomial sampling. It then computes view-specific embeddings (LightGCN for the interaction view; rationale-aware aggregation for the KG view), maps them into a shared space with two MLPs, and optimizes a modified InfoNCE-style loss with one random negative per view and temperature τ, yielding noise-resistant cross-view alignment."}]}
